            . I am the wife of 
               <persName id="t18290910-218-person2003">
                  Thomas 
                  Pratt
               <interp inst="t18290910-218-person2003" type="surname" value="Pratt"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-218-person2003" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-218-person2003" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             - we live in Windmill-street, Tottenham-court-road; the prisoner lodged with me, and was taken on Monday, the 10th of August - her box was found in my house, which had been brought there with her.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-218-person2004">
                  HANNAH 
                  MUNDAY
               <interp inst="t18290910-218-person2004" type="surname" value="MUNDAY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-218-person2004" type="given" value="HANNAH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-218-person2004" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of Jacob Munday - we live in Burn's-place, Edgware-road; I can see from my bed-room into Mrs. Allen's house. I saw the prisoner on Mrs. Allen's fence on the 27th of July - the fence broke, and she went over into another garden - she then stood upon the fence some time - I called to her, but she did not answer me; she then went into Mr. Burke's wash-house, got on the files, and into the loft of Mrs. Allen's house - I waited about an hour and a half; she did not come out - I then went to bed; I told Mrs. Allen of it on the Friday evening.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-218-person2005">
                  MARY 
                  ALLEN
               <interp inst="t18290910-218-person2005" type="surname" value="ALLEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-218-person2005" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-218-person2005" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the Sunday night, the 26th, I tried a little room by the side of my bed-room, and found it locked - I thought my niece had taken the key; in the morning, when she came, I said, "Why did you lock that door?" she said. I did not;" she opened the door, we went in, and missed her bonnet, a cornelian necklace, a pair of ear-rings, two brooches, a silver knife, two shirt-pins, and a great many other things, which I have never seen since - I had seen them safe on the Saturday or Sunday, in the bureau; I know the bureau was fast on the Sunday - whoever took the things must have secreted themselves in the house; the bureau was wrenched all to pieces - the prisoner knew the bureau; and in her father's life time, if we had a little money, it was always put there - I went to Mrs. Pratt's house, and saw the box which my daughter had brought there; I saw a great many things of mine there, and a great number of duplicates - the officer took her; I do not recollect that she said any thing.</p>

               <p>Prisoner. I leave it to the mercy of the Court and my mother.</p>
               <p>JURY to MRS. ALLEN Q. Did you turn your daughter out of doors? A. No; she has been robbing me these five years successively - I have seen her but once since her father's death, and then she was in a situation.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18290910-218-verdict1207" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290910-218-verdict1207" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 18.</p>
